  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# M5 Forecasting \u2014 CPG Sales EDA\n\nExploratory data analysis on the Walmart M5 dataset (`sales_train_validation.csv`).\n\n**Dataset:** 30,490 time series \u00d7 1,913 daily columns, covering 3 categories: FOODS, HOBBIES, HOUSEHOLD across 10 Walmart stores in CA, TX, WI."
      ],
      "id": "md-intro"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport warnings\nwarnings.filterwarnings('ignore')\nprint('Libraries loaded successfully.')"
      ],
      "id": "imports"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": ["## 1. Load Data"],
      "id": "md-load"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "DATA_PATH = '/kaggle/input/m5-forecasting-accuracy/sales_train_validation.csv'\ndf = pd.read_csv(DATA_PATH)\nprint(f'Shape: {df.shape}')"
      ],
      "id": "load-data"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": ["## 2. Basic Inspection"],
      "id": "md-inspect"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": ["df.head()"],
      "id": "head"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": ["df.info(verbose=False, show_counts=True)"],
      "id": "info"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "cols_to_describe = ['d_1', 'd_100', 'd_500', 'd_1000', 'd_1913']\ndf[cols_to_describe].describe().round(2)"
      ],
      "id": "describe"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 3. Melt to Long Format \u2014 (item_id, store_id, date) \u00d7 sales\n\nThe raw file has one row per product-store pair and one column per day (`d_1` ... `d_1913`). \nWe melt it into a tidy long DataFrame: each row is one observation for one item-store on one day."
      ],
      "id": "md-melt"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "id_cols = ['id', 'item_id', 'dept_id', 'cat_id', 'store_id', 'state_id']\nday_cols = [c for c in df.columns if c.startswith('d_')]\n\nlong = df.melt(\n    id_vars=id_cols,\n    value_vars=day_cols,\n    var_name='d',\n    value_name='sales'\n)\n\nlong['day_num'] = long['d'].str.extract(r'(\\d+)').astype(int)\nlong = long.sort_values(['item_id', 'store_id', 'day_num']).reset_index(drop=True)\nprint(f'Long DataFrame shape: {long.shape}')\nlong.head(10)"
      ],
      "id": "melt"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": ["## 4. Confirm ~30,000 Unique (item, store) Series"],
      "id": "md-unique"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "n_series = long.groupby(['item_id', 'store_id']).ngroups\nprint(f'Unique (item_id, store_id) series: {n_series:,}')\nassert 29_000 <= n_series <= 31_000\nprint('Confirmed ~30,000 series.')"
      ],
      "id": "unique-series"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": ["## 5. Total Sales Per Category"],
      "id": "md-category"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "category_totals = long.groupby('cat_id')['sales'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)\nprint(category_totals.to_string())\ncategory_totals.plot(kind='bar', title='Total Sales by Category', ylabel='Units', rot=0, figsize=(7,4), color=['#e07b39','#3a86ff','#43aa8b'])\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "category-totals"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": ["## 6. Daily Total Sales for FOODS"],
      "id": "md-foods"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "foods_daily = long[long['cat_id']=='FOODS'].groupby('day_num')['sales'].sum().reset_index()\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14,4))\nax.plot(foods_daily['day_num'], foods_daily['sales'], lw=0.8, color='#e07b39', alpha=0.85)\nax.set(title='Daily Total Sales - FOODS (all stores)', xlabel='Day index', ylabel='Units')\nax.grid(axis='y', ls='--', alpha=0.5)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.savefig('foods_daily_sales.png', dpi=150)\nplt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "foods-daily"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 7. Forecast Evaluation Setup\n\nWe evaluate both baselines on a **28-day holdout** (days 1886\u20131913), matching the M5 competition evaluation window.\n\n- **Train**: d_1 \u2013 d_1885 (1,885 days)\n- **Test / holdout**: d_1886 \u2013 d_1913 (28 days)\n\nWMAPE is computed per-series and aggregated with sales-volume weights, matching the official M5 metric."
      ],
      "id": "md-forecast-setup"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# ── Forecast evaluation constants ──────────────────────────────────────────\nH          = 28          # forecast horizon (days)\nTRAIN_END  = 1885        # last training day index\nTEST_START = TRAIN_END + 1   # 1886\nTEST_END   = 1913\n\n# Pivot long \u2192 wide for easy per-series slicing\nwide = (\n    long[['item_id', 'store_id', 'day_num', 'sales']]\n    .pivot_table(index=['item_id', 'store_id'], columns='day_num', values='sales')\n)\nwide.columns = wide.columns.astype(int)\nwide = wide.sort_index(axis=1)\n\nprint(f'Wide pivot shape: {wide.shape}  (series \u00d7 days)')\n\ntrain_wide = wide.loc[:, :TRAIN_END]\ntest_wide  = wide.loc[:, TEST_START:TEST_END]\nprint(f'Train cols: {train_wide.shape[1]}  |  Test cols: {test_wide.shape[1]}')\n\ntrain_volume = train_wide.sum(axis=1)\nprint(f'Total training volume: {train_volume.sum():,.0f} units')"
      ],
      "id": "forecast-setup"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 8. Last-Value (Na\u00efve) Forecast\n\nThe **last-value** (random-walk / na\u00efve) baseline repeats the most-recently observed value for all $h$ steps:\n\n$$\\hat{y}_{t+h} = y_{T}$$\n\nwhere $T =$ last training day (d\_1885) and $h = 1, \\ldots, 28$."
      ],
      "id": "md-last-value"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# ── Last-Value forecast ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nlast_obs    = train_wide.iloc[:, -1]          # d_1885 for every series\nlv_forecast = pd.DataFrame(\n    np.tile(last_obs.values[:, None], (1, H)),\n    index=wide.index,\n    columns=test_wide.columns\n)\nlv_errors = (lv_forecast - test_wide).abs()\nprint('Last-Value forecast generated.')\nprint(f'  Forecast shape : {lv_forecast.shape}')\nprint(f'  Mean abs error (unweighted): {lv_errors.values.mean():.4f}')"
      ],
      "id": "last-value"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 9. Seasonal-Na\u00efve (sNa\u00efve-7) Forecast\n\nThe **seasonal-na\u00efve** baseline copies the value from the same weekday one season ago:\n\n$$\\hat{y}_{t+h} = y_{T - m + ((h-1) \\bmod m) + 1}$$\n\nwith period $m = 7$ (weekly). The last complete training week is tiled cyclically across the 28-day horizon."
      ],
      "id": "md-snaive"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# ── Seasonal-Na\u00efve (period m=7) forecast ────────────────────────────────────\nm = 7   # weekly seasonality\nlast_season   = train_wide.iloc[:, -m:]           # d_1879 \u2026 d_1885 (shape n_series \u00d7 7)\nsnaive_values = np.tile(last_season.values, (1, H // m))   # (n_series, 28)\nsnaive_forecast = pd.DataFrame(snaive_values, index=wide.index, columns=test_wide.columns)\nsnaive_errors   = (snaive_forecast - test_wide).abs()\nprint('Seasonal-Na\u00efve (m=7) forecast generated.')\nprint(f'  Forecast shape : {snaive_forecast.shape}')\nprint(f'  Mean abs error (unweighted): {snaive_errors.values.mean():.4f}')"
      ],
      "id": "snaive"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 10. WMAPE Comparison\n\n**WMAPE** weights each series by its training-period sales volume:\n\n$$\\text{WMAPE} = \\frac{\\sum_i w_i \\cdot \\text{MAE}_i}{\\sum_i w_i \\cdot \\bar{y}_i^{\\text{train}}}$$\n\nwhere $w_i$ = training volume of series $i$ and $\\bar{y}_i^{\\text{train}}$ = mean training sales."
      ],
      "id": "md-wmape"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "def wmape(errors_df, weights):\n    mae      = errors_df.mean(axis=1)\n    mean_act = train_wide.mean(axis=1)\n    mask = mean_act > 0\n    w = weights[mask]\n    return (w * mae[mask]).sum() / (w * mean_act[mask]).sum()\n\nlv_wmape     = wmape(lv_errors,     train_volume)\nsnaive_wmape = wmape(snaive_errors, train_volume)\n\nresults = pd.DataFrame({\n    'Model'    : ['Last-Value (Na\u00efve)', 'Seasonal-Na\u00efve (m=7)'],\n    'WMAPE'    : [lv_wmape, snaive_wmape],\n    'WMAPE (%)': [lv_wmape * 100, snaive_wmape * 100],\n})\nprint('=== Baseline Forecast WMAPE Results ===')\nprint(results.to_string(index=False))\n\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,4))\nbars = ax.bar(results['Model'], results['WMAPE (%)'], color=['#3a86ff','#e07b39'], width=0.5)\nfor bar, val in zip(bars, results['WMAPE (%)']):  \n    ax.text(bar.get_x()+bar.get_width()/2, bar.get_height()+0.3, f'{val:.2f}%', ha='center', fontweight='bold')\nax.set(title='WMAPE by Baseline (28-day holdout)', ylabel='WMAPE (%)', ylim=(0, max(results['WMAPE (%)'])*1.25))\nax.grid(axis='y', ls='--', alpha=0.4)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.savefig('wmape_comparison.png', dpi=150)\nplt.show()\nprint('Chart saved to wmape_comparison.png')"
      ],
      "id": "wmape-comparison"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 11. Findings\n\n### Results Summary\n\n| Model | WMAPE |\n|---|---|\n| Last-Value (Na\u00efve) | *see cell output above* |\n| Seasonal-Na\u00efve (m = 7) | *see cell output above* |\n\n### Key Observations\n\n**Last-Value (Na\u00efve) baseline**  \nForecasts every step as the single most recent sales observation (d\_1885). It correctly captures the current demand level but ignores all weekly structure. Since Walmart CPG sales exhibit strong day-of-week seasonality, this baseline systematically over- or under-predicts depending on which weekday each holdout period falls on, resulting in a relatively high WMAPE.\n\n**Seasonal-Na\u00efve (m = 7) baseline**  \nRepeats the last complete 7-day training cycle for each of the 4 holdout weeks, capturing weekend peaks and weekday troughs with zero parameter estimation. For retail demand, day-of-week effects are the dominant short-horizon driver, so this baseline typically yields a noticeably lower WMAPE than the plain na\u00efve model.\n\n**WMAPE interpretation**  \nWMAPE is volume-weighted, so high-selling FOODS series dominate the aggregate score. Both baselines serve as meaningful benchmarks: any ML model (LightGBM, Prophet, DeepAR) must beat the seasonal-na\u00efve WMAPE to justify added complexity.\n\n### Next Steps\n\n1. **7-day rolling-mean baseline** \u2013 often closes most of the gap between na\u00efve and a trained model.\n2. **Feature engineering** \u2013 calendar effects (day-of-week, month, SNAP flags, holiday dummies).\n3. **Hierarchical reconciliation** \u2013 M5 evaluates all aggregation levels; ensure bottom-up coherence.\n4. **LightGBM / XGBoost** \u2013 gradient-boosted trees with lag features have consistently topped M5 leaderboards."
      ],
      "id": "md-findings"
    }
  ]
}
